UCSF coronavirus expert Dr. Bob Wachter sounded the alarm bells Monday around California&#39;s surge in coronavirus cases.
   &#34;Let’s talk California,&#34; Wachter, chair of UCSF&#39;s department of medicine, wrote on Twitter. &#34;Until recently, our state managed to do so well that our experience has been dubbed The California Miracle. But let’s say it clearly: The Miracle is over. The sooner we acknowledge that, the better off we’ll be.&#34;
      Wachter has become a well-recognized expert on COVID-19 by posting regular and lengthy threads on Twitter that unpack complicated matters and provide an insider&#39;s look on the pandemic.
   In his  Monday thread featuring 24 tweets, Wachter tells the story of how California has gone from a state with remarkably low spread to one where hospital beds are filling up fast. &#34;Overall, the past 2 weeks are bleak: new cases doubled, hospitalizations ↑43%, ICU pts ↑37%, &amp; test positivity rate from 4.4%→5.5%,&#34; he shared.
   1/ Covid ( @UCSF) Chronicles, Day 104  Let’s talk California. Until recently, our state managed to do so well that our experience has been dubbed The California Miracle. But let’s say it clearly: The Miracle is over. The sooner we acknowledge that, the better off we’ll be.
— Bob Wachter (@Bob_Wachter)  June 30, 2020
   Wachter pointed to other states where cases are spiking such as Texas, Arizona and Florida and wrote, &#34;One can easily point to leadership malpractice by governors and other politicians. They doled out misinformation about Covid and failed to require evidence-based practices, like masking, to prevent spread. Unforgivable.&#34;
              California is experiencing a different scenario, he said. &#34;Our leaders acted responsibly,&#34; wrote Wachter. &#34;And Californians mostly did too. But around Memorial Day, standards were relaxed, people (yes, mostly young ones) got complacent, and – after a string of lucky breaks – our luck ran out. Now it’s our time.&#34;
       As many experts have concluded, Wachter noted the state&#39;s early action in the pandemic contributed to the low rates of spread in March, April and May.
   &#34;But we made it through 3 mths remarkably unscathed,&#34; he wrote. &#34;On June 1, CA had ~100,000 total cases &amp; 4,000 deaths. In contrast, NY State, with half our population, had ~370K cases &amp; 30,000 deaths. “The California Miracle” narrative was born; I contributed to it,&#34; Wachter wrote.
   The story has since changed, and Wachter said that &#34;a bump in cases was expected&#34; but few, including him, &#34;expected it to be so fast and widespread.&#34;
   &#34;So even in CA, with masking &amp; distancing mandates, many people got sloppy,&#34; he wrote. &#34;On top of that, our lucky streak came to a screeching halt. One horrific example is San Quentin prison, just north of SF, where the number of infected prisoners just topped 1000.&#34;
      Wachter noted that San Francisco has yet to see the spike other California counties are experiencing, but this could change. &#34;SF not surging, but warning signs,&#34; he wrote. &#34;@UCSFHospitals 16 pts, 5 on vents; ~double 2 wks ago. In SF, cases and hospitalizations up; most of bump in hospital pts is transfers from elsewhere. Forgive the metaphor, but if somebody sneezes in LA, we’ll ultimately catch a cold in SF.&#34;
   Gov. Gavin Newsom also expressed alarm over California&#39;s spike in his press briefing Monday. Wachter noted, &#34;The message from the governor was crystal clear: if we don’t turn things around, we may find ourselves back to widespread shelter-in-place soon.&#34;
